Date: 0/0/1946
Source: Journal of the Polynesian Society
Author:
Vol / Page: 55/160
Edition:
Quote: <i>whare-kura,</i> school of learning; building where esoteric law was imparted to fit pupils: knowledge of karakia and other valuable lore was called kura, and kura also means treasure, since with the Maori, knowledge was above rubies (or their equivalent, pounamu).
Notes: Andersen Maori Words in English

Date: 0/0/1947
Source: Maori and Pakeha in North Otago
Author: STEVENSON
Vol / Page: 84
Edition:
Quote: The last session of a Whare-kura in the South Island was held at Moeraki in 1868. The Whare-kura was a school in which selected students were instructed in religion, ritual, tribal lore, agriculture, and the art of warfare etc.
